    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay, i get the theory behind it. but lets get more specific for the debate. if i were arguing this in class, how would i argue that these policies weren't just about exclusion, but were actually a \"rational\" way to protect the integrity of the suburban middle class? like, focus on the idea that rapid change or integration would fundamentally destabilize the economic and social structures that allowed the country to thrive. can you flesh out that specific viewpoint—making it sound like a legitimate sociopolitical philosophy for the time? i need to be able to present it without sounding like i'm just repeating old tropes, so make it sound like a reasoned, structural argument.",
